ided free to the population has produced a widespread perception of patients as passive consumers of health care. This book explores how we may renew for our times the collective compact that created our public services in the 1940s. Voices from service users and service providers show how this can be done. They offer testimony of what goes wrong and what can be put right when working together becomes the norm. Sections explore new ways of living and working with long-term conditions, more meaningful and effective approaches to service redesign, use of information technology, leadership, co-production and creating and accounting for quality. Accessible to a wide range of readers, with short, accessible contributions, this is a book to provoke and inspire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPublic health advisory groups. 0aPublic healthxCitizen participation. 0aPublic healthzGreat Britain. 0aPublic health. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aAnsell, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBacon, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarle, Nan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Rohhss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Georgina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go